From the onset, Rouder and Morey (2012) are explicit about the fact that “these priors are subjective [emphasis added] and convey specified prior beliefs about the alternative under consideration” (Rouder & Morey, 2012, p. 883; see also Rouder et al., 2016). This is a crucial point given that Bayes factors are strongly dependent on the choice of priors, especially the prior for the targeted effect (see Du et al., 2019; Rouder & Morey, 2012; Rouder et al., 2009, 2012). This dependency is such that radically different Bayes factors can be obtained for the same data by simply varying the prior chosen (e.g., Du et al., 2019). Given that this subjective choice is highly consequential, researchers are well advised to be judicious.Table 2
