The priors proposed here combine both types of considerations. In terms of formal constraints, they satisfy desirable consistency and invariance conditions (see Section “Properties of Bayes factors based on effect-size and moment priors”). On the substantive side, they incorporate a preference for effects of a prespecified effect size and a penalty for overly large effect sizes. That said, they do not prioritize any specific effect pattern (e.g., the specific shape of an interaction or, in the case of two-sided t tests, the specific direction of an effect) over any other pattern. Without getting into a discussion of which kinds of priors are best (see, e.g., Berger, 2006; Torsen, 2015), we believe that the priors proposed here strike a balance that is quite appealing to any researcher looking for a general solution that does not commit them to strong substantive assumptions.Table 4
