				\begin{document}$$H_1$$\end{document}H1. This train of thought raised the question of how to transform the outcomes of significance tests onto the Bayes factor metric, leading to the novel insight that default, effect-size, and moment Bayes factors are all instances of test-statistic-based Bayes factors (Johnson, 2005, 2008, but see Footnote 17). The test-statistic-based Bayes factor is a useful approach to Bayes factor-based hypothesis tests that allows one to compute valid Bayes factors for most hypothesis testing problems for which an effect-size measure has been proposed and test power can be computed. This approach has the potential to lead to a software program for conducting Bayes factor analyses of similar scope as the famous G*Power 3 program (Faul et al., 2007).

fn.p:
Whereas the present manuscript focuses on Bayesian hypothesis testing via Bayes factors, we note that another principled approach to Bayesian hypothesis testing relies on the posterior distribution of parameters (e.g., Kruschke, 2015, chap. 12). A discussion of the relative merits of both approaches is beyond the scope of this manuscript (see, e.g., Tendeiro & Kiers, 2019; van Ravenwzaaij & Wagenmakers, 2022). Moreover, the exposition will focus on non-directional tests of strict null hypotheses (i.e., \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
