				\begin{document}$$H_0: \theta = 0$$\end{document}H0:θ=0), but the methods developed here are easily applied to test directional alternative hypotheses as well as to test interval hypotheses specified as regions of effects smaller (or larger) than a predetermined size (e.g., in terms of regions of practical equivalence, Kruschke, 2015, chap. 12) as well as to test simple (point) hypotheses specified in terms of fixed values \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
