What does it mean for a prior distribution to be implied by other priors? Consider as an example, Cohen’s effect-size parameter \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$f^2$$\end{document}f2 for regression problems. It is not itself a model parameter, but it is defined as a function of the model parameters, for which prior distributions are specified. Its prior distribution can therefore be computed from the prior distributions of the model parameters that define it and in this sense, its prior distribution is implied by these other parameters’ priors.

According to Cohen (1988), “it is not generally necessary to make provision for \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\varvec{w}$$\end{document}w [w] greater than .90” (p.218), justifying the use of relatively small standard deviations.

